---
import RootLayout from "../layouts/RootLayout.astro"
---

<RootLayout
  title="Astrolabe — about the Pioneer plaque"
  description="The history behind the 1972 Pioneer plaque pulsar map, Frank Drake's triangulation scheme, and why Astrolabe picks the pulsars it does."
  path="/about"
>
  <div class="min-h-svh flex flex-col">
    <header class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 px-5 py-3 border-b border-foreground/10 shrink-0">
      <a
        href="/"
        class="text-[12px] text-foreground hover:text-foreground/70 transition"
        style="font-family: var(--font-display)"
      >
        ASTROLABE
      </a>
      <a
        href="/"
        class="text-[10px] text-foreground/50 hover:text-foreground transition"
        aria-label="back to the map"
      >
        ← back to the map
      </a>
    </header>

    <main
      id="main"
      class="max-w-2xl mx-auto w-full px-5 sm:px-8 py-10 sm:py-16 flex flex-col gap-10"
    >
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <p class="text-[9px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-foreground/45">
          1972 · pioneer 10 · a message from nowhere in particular
        </p>
        <h1
          class="text-[32px] sm:text-[42px] leading-[1.05] text-foreground"
          style="font-family: var(--font-display)"
        >
          how to write an address for the solar system
        </h1>
        <p class="text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-foreground/75 max-w-prose">
          In March 1972, NASA launched Pioneer 10 on a trajectory that would
          eventually carry it out of the solar system. Bolted to its antenna
          support strut was a gold-anodised aluminium plaque engraved with a
          pictogram intended to identify <em>where</em> and <em>when</em>
          the spacecraft came from — without relying on any language, any
          number system, or any culture that a reader would need to share
          with us.
        </p>
        <p class="text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-foreground/75 max-w-prose">
          The plaque was designed in three weeks by Frank Drake, Carl Sagan,
          and Linda Salzman Sagan. The central question: what landmarks in the
          galaxy are stable, detectable, and unambiguous enough that any
          spacefaring reader — ours, or someone else's — could locate the
          Sun by their relative positions?
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2
          class="text-[20px] text-foreground leading-tight"
          style="font-family: var(--font-display)"
        >
          why pulsars
        </h2>
        <p class="text-[12px] leading-relaxed text-foreground/75 max-w-prose">
          Pulsars are rotating neutron stars that sweep a beam of radio
          emission past Earth at staggeringly precise intervals — periods
          ranging from about one millisecond to a few seconds, and stable
          enough that their slow spindown can be reasoned about millions of
          years into the past.
        </p>
        <p class="text-[12px] leading-relaxed text-foreground/75 max-w-prose">
          Every pulsar Drake picked has its own unique fingerprint: a period
          that any observer can measure, and a distance that can be inferred.
          Taken together, the relative angles and distances from the observer
          to a handful of pulsars form a triangulation map that resolves to
          essentially one point in the galaxy — the Sun — even after
          thousands of years of proper motion.
        </p>
        <p class="text-[12px] leading-relaxed text-foreground/75 max-w-prose">
          The binary tick marks at the end of each line encode the pulsar's
          period in units of the hydrogen-21cm spin-flip transition — a
          frequency defined by atomic physics, not by any cultural
          convention. "We know what hydrogen does; here is how long this
          pulsar's cycle lasts in those units." Read the binary, look up the
          pulsars in your own catalogues, and you can place the author's
          home system with high confidence.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2
          class="text-[20px] text-foreground leading-tight"
          style="font-family: var(--font-display)"
        >
          what astrolabe does
        </h2>
        <p class="text-[12px] leading-relaxed text-foreground/75 max-w-prose">
          Astrolabe reproduces the plaque's triangulation map for any observer
          in the galaxy — not just the Sun. Pick a star, a custom galactic
          coordinate, or any object SIMBAD can resolve, and the app recomputes
          the best fourteen pulsars from <em>that</em> vantage point using
          several selection strategies.
        </p>

        <div class="flex flex-col gap-2 text-[11px] leading-relaxed text-foreground/70 max-w-prose">
          <div>
            <span class="text-foreground">gdop</span>
            <span class="text-foreground/55">
              — greedy geometric-dilution-of-precision. Pick pulsars that
              together produce the smallest triangulation error. Default.
              Matches what you would actually want if you were designing a
              navigation system.
            </span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-foreground">fastest</span>
            <span class="text-foreground/55">
              — shortest rotation periods. Millisecond pulsars are the most
              precise clocks in the universe; a set of them gives the most
              stable binary signatures.
            </span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-foreground">closest</span>
            <span class="text-foreground/55">
              — nearest to the observer. Short lines mean the smallest
              absolute position errors, at the cost of poor angular
              coverage.
            </span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-foreground">longest</span>
            <span class="text-foreground/55">
              — furthest from the observer. Long lines provide the best
              angular leverage for coarse localisation.
            </span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-foreground">stable</span>
            <span class="text-foreground/55">
              — lowest spindown rate. Pulsars whose periods change the
              slowest stay usable as clocks across the longest time spans.
            </span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-foreground">random</span>
            <span class="text-foreground/55">
              — a reshuffle from the full catalogue. Useful for sanity
              checks and for seeing how much worse an unplanned
              triangulation set can look.
            </span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2
          class="text-[20px] text-foreground leading-tight"
          style="font-family: var(--font-display)"
        >
          reading a pulsar line
        </h2>
        <ul class="flex flex-col gap-1.5 text-[11px] leading-relaxed text-foreground/70 max-w-prose list-none pl-0">
          <li>
            <span class="text-foreground">line length</span>
            <span class="text-foreground/55">
              — projected distance to the pulsar from the observer, linear
              in kiloparsecs.
            </span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="text-foreground">line direction</span>
            <span class="text-foreground/55">
              — galactic longitude. The long horizontal line points toward
              the galactic centre.
            </span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="text-foreground">binary ticks</span>
            <span class="text-foreground/55">
              — the pulsar's spin period, most-significant bit first, in
              hydrogen-21cm units. A <em>|</em> is a 1, a <em>−</em> is a 0.
            </span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="text-foreground">time-machine slider</span>
            <span class="text-foreground/55">
              — applies synthetic proper motion and spindown up to ±10 Myr.
              The pulsars drift, the periods evolve, the binary digits flip.
            </span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2
          class="text-[20px] text-foreground leading-tight"
          style="font-family: var(--font-display)"
        >
          data
        </h2>
        <p class="text-[12px] leading-relaxed text-foreground/75 max-w-prose">
          Pulsar data comes from the
          <a
            href="https://www.atnf.csiro.au/research/pulsar/psrcat/"
            class="underline decoration-foreground/30 hover:decoration-foreground text-foreground"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noreferrer"
            >ATNF Pulsar Catalogue v2.7.0</a
          >
          — 3,924 pulsars, each with a spin period, spindown rate, and
          distance estimate. The curated star list is a hand-picked set of
          notable objects for the picker; any other star can be resolved on
          demand through the
          <a
            href="https://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/simbad/"
            class="underline decoration-foreground/30 hover:decoration-foreground text-foreground"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noreferrer"
            >SIMBAD</a
          >
          fallback.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2
          class="text-[20px] text-foreground leading-tight"
          style="font-family: var(--font-display)"
        >
          further reading
        </h2>
        <ul
          class="flex flex-col gap-1 text-[11px] leading-relaxed text-foreground/70 max-w-prose list-none pl-0"
        >
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pioneer_plaque"
              class="underline decoration-foreground/30 hover:decoration-foreground text-foreground/90"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noreferrer"
              >the pioneer plaque (wikipedia)</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/missions/pioneer-10"
              class="underline decoration-foreground/30 hover:decoration-foreground text-foreground/90"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noreferrer"
              >pioneer 10 — nasa/jpl</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Drake"
              class="underline decoration-foreground/30 hover:decoration-foreground text-foreground/90"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noreferrer"
              >frank drake (wikipedia)</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://github.com/codeptor/astrolabe"
              class="underline decoration-foreground/30 hover:decoration-foreground text-foreground/90"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noreferrer"
              >astrolabe — source on github</a
            >
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </main>
  </div>
</RootLayout>
